ble sources and use them efficiently. The imperative for a fourth energy transition comes from dangers related to climate change, geopolitical tensions, documented health and environmental effects, and long-term depletion of today’s sources. John H. Perkins argues that a future in which current levels of energy service benefits are sustained can come only from investments in the technologies needed to bring about a fourth energy transition. Changing Energy envisions a viable post–fossil fuel economy and identifies the barriers to be overcome.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnergy consumption. 0aFossil fuels. 0aPower resources. 0aRenewable energy sources. 0aSustainable development. 7aSCIENCE / Energy.2bisacsh  abig four fuels.  abiofuels.  aclimate change.  acoal.  adepletion of resources.  aenergy economies.  aenergy economy.  aenergy efficiency.  aenergy use and depletion.  aenergy.  afossil fuels.  agas.  ageopolitical tensions.  ahealth and environmental effects of energy.  ahuman energy needs.  anuclear power.  aoil.  apost fossil fuel economy.  apower resources.  apower.  aprimary fuels.  arenewable energy.  arenewable resources.  arenewable sources.  asustainable energy.  auranium.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028779240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096284240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962842/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles